# Transaction Monitoring Workflow Design

## Project Objective

The purpose of this project is not only to develop SQL-based AML detection scenarios but also to simulate the operational workflow of a Transaction Monitoring (TM) system.

Real-world TM systems do not stop at identifying unusual activity. Alerts generated by detection rules must be reviewed, investigated, dispositioned, and documented by analysts before a final decision is reached.

This document outlines the simulated TM workflow used in this project.

---

# Transaction Monitoring Lifecycle

Rule
↓
Alert
↓
Case Creation
↓
Investigation
↓
Disposition
↓
Case Closure

---

# Stage 1 – Detection Rule

Detection rules identify customers whose transaction behaviour meets predefined criteria.

Examples from this project:

| Investigation    | Scenario                      |
| ---------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Investigation 01 | Funnel Account Behaviour      |
| Investigation 02 | Dormant Account Reactivation  |
| Investigation 03 | Structuring Detection         |
| Investigation 04 | Transaction Velocity Analysis |
| Investigation 05 | Rapid Movement of Funds       |

Detection rules are implemented using SQL and are executed against customer and transaction datasets.

---

# Stage 2 – Alert Generation

Customers meeting rule criteria are converted into alerts.

An alert represents a potential risk indicator requiring analyst review.

Example:

| Alert ID | Rule Name                | Customer ID |
| -------- | ------------------------ | ----------- |
| ALT0001  | Funnel Account Behaviour | CUST00260   |
| ALT0002  | Dormant Reactivation     | CUST00376   |
| ALT0003  | Structuring Detection    | CUST00105   |

At this stage no conclusion has been reached regarding suspicious activity.

The alert simply indicates that the customer meets predefined rule criteria.

---

# Stage 3 – Case Creation

Alerts that warrant review are converted into investigation cases.

A case provides a structured framework for documenting investigative findings.

Example:

| Case ID  | Alert ID | Customer ID |
| -------- | -------- | ----------- |
| CASE0001 | ALT0001  | CUST00260   |
| CASE0002 | ALT0002  | CUST00376   |

A single alert typically creates one case.

Multiple alerts relating to the same customer may also be consolidated into a single case.

---

# Stage 4 – Investigation

The investigator reviews:

* Customer profile
* Risk rating
* Transaction history
* Transaction volumes
* Historical behaviour
* Counterparty activity
* Rule-specific findings

Examples from this project include:

## Funnel Account Investigation

Review Criteria:

* High incoming transaction volume
* High outgoing transaction volume
* Multiple counterparties
* High pass-through behaviour

Example Finding:

Customer received funds from multiple counterparties and transferred more than 80% of incoming funds onwards.

---

## Dormant Account Reactivation

Review Criteria:

* Long inactivity period
* Significant activity after reactivation
* Transaction volume exceeding expected behaviour

Example Finding:

Customer inactive for more than 390 days.

Following reactivation, 30-day transaction volume exceeded expected monthly volume by more than 60 times.

---

## Structuring Investigation

Review Criteria:

* Multiple cash deposits on the same day
* Aggregate daily cash activity
* Transaction volume inconsistent with expected behaviour

Example Finding:

Customer conducted multiple cash deposits below typical reporting thresholds within a single day.

---

# Stage 5 – Disposition

After review, the investigator assigns a disposition.

Possible outcomes include:

| Disposition                     | Description                                      |
| ------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| False Positive                  | Alert generated but behaviour appears legitimate |
| Closed – No Issue               | No suspicious indicators identified              |
| Monitoring Required             | Activity should be monitored going forward       |
| Escalated                       | Additional review required                       |
| Enhanced Due Diligence Required | Further customer review required                 |
| SAR Recommended                 | Escalation for suspicious activity reporting     |

Examples from this project:

| Investigation            | Likely Disposition |
| ------------------------ | ------------------ |
| Funnel Account Behaviour | Escalated          |
| Dormant Reactivation     | Escalated          |
| Structuring Detection    | Escalated          |
| Velocity Analysis        | False Positive     |
| Rapid Movement Analysis  | False Positive     |

---

# Stage 6 – Case Closure

Following investigation and disposition, the case is closed.

Case documentation should include:

* Investigation summary
* Supporting evidence
* Key findings
* Final disposition
* Investigator notes

Example:

"Customer exhibited significant post-reactivation transaction volume following a prolonged dormant period. Transaction activity exceeded expected customer behaviour. Escalated for further review."

